        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 263. <placeName type="sitename">Ardmore</placeName>
                    I</name>, Co. <placeName type="county">Waterford</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                        target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WA040-008005-"
                        >WA040-008005-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Ecclesiastical</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>Early ecclesiastical site (<hi rend="italic"><placeName xml:lang="ga">Ard
                        Mór/Uí Seasta</placeName></hi> –
                            <placeName type="townland">Ardocheasty</placeName> townland). Early features at this
                        site include St Declan's oratory, cathedral ruins (Romanesque), round tower,
                        and 1 other ogham stone (<ref
                            target="search.php?ciic=265">CIIC
                            265</ref>) still on site inside cathedral walls and 1 other now in the
                        National Museum of Ireland (<ref
                            target="search.php?ciic=264"
                            >CIIC 264</ref>). </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>
                       <q>The stone is chipped on the top, probably by the masons who adapted it as
                            building stone, but is otherwise in good condition</q>. <rs
                            type="material"/>Greenstone, <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.27</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.28</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.30</measure>m
                                <lb/> (converted from <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp">258</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>According to <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                            (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >258</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> the stone <q>bears two independent inscriptions in Ogham: the first, on two
                            angles, (up-down), <rs type="execution">pocked</rs>; the second, on a third angle, [up,]
                                <rs type="execution">chiselled</rs></q>. <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991"
                                ><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope
                                    type="pp">65</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, however, appears to regard it as a single inscription.</p> 
                    <p>According to <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister
                            </author> (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >259</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> the gap in the <q>first inscription</q> between
                        MAQI and MUCOI gives sufficient space for a short name. He adds that <q>the
                            MU and C1 of MUCOI are lost. Below NETA the angle is spalled, but the
                            fracture must have preceded the cutting of the inscription, as the
                            lettering follows the present line of the edge</q>. The final I of MAQI
                        is not visible to <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991"
                                ><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope
                                type="pp">65</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> but faint traces of 4 of the 5 notches can be seen on the 3D model.</p>
                    <p>With regard to the <q>second inscription</q> <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                ><bibl><author>Macalister </author> (<date when="1945">1945</date>,
                                <biblScope type="pp">259-60</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> says that <q>there is
                            nothing surviving after the final B: vague scratches on the fourth angle
                            exist, but are too indefinite to suggest a continuation of the
                            epitaph</q>. </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <persName><w lemma="LUGUDECAS">LUGUDECCAS</w></persName>
                    <w type="formula" lemma="MAQI">MAQ<unclear reason="worn"
                        >I</unclear></w>/<gap reason="lost"/><w type="formula" lemma="MUCOI"><supplied reason="lost" cert="high">MU</supplied>/COI</w>
                    <persName><w lemma="NETA-SEGAMONAS">NETA-SEGAMONAS</w></persName>/
                    <w>DOLATI</w>
                    <w>BIGAISGOB...</w>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <ab>
                    <q>of Luguid son of ...? descendant of Nad-Segamon</q>
                    </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
